na. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/16/02 9:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=520.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re:Would a secret Orion programme be feasable?</span><hr size=1> Well, that would work except for a couple of points.<br>
<br>
1. The shock of the launch would be detected by the seismic detection stations that were meant to detect an underground test, and the Orion would have to be underground to not be detected. Remember, these same stations could differentiate between the HTP tank bursting in a torpedo and the warhead cook off on the kursk.<br>
<br>
2. The orbiting nuclear detection satt's would detect the airburst energy that the pusherplate did not use, which is a tremendous amount. These same satts were put into place to help enforce the atmospheric test ban treaty.<br>
<br>
3. I would bet very good money that with that since they captured our spyplane over a year ago, that we have been keeping a very close eye on them. most likely overflights by spysatts. The satts can pickout a nuclear missile silo, I think they would be able to detect something a little larger<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
4. For a project this massive, not even china could keep it a total secret for long, and most likely, the US and/or other countries would be wondering why there was a step up in warhead production, which could be detected by the thermal output of their reactors that we know about.<br>
<br>
Conclusion: There is a possibility that it could be carried off without anyone knowing it, but the possibility is remote. Someone would know something was going on, but they may not know what it is exactly. <br>
<br>
*btw, what effect would a 20 megaton airburst have on a Orion if it was attacked?<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 272<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/18/02 2:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=520.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: a secret Orion programme</span><hr size=1> By far, the biggest problem for someone (not the US, maybe) is pulse-unit production. A heck of a lot of work going on, along the lines of something remarkably resembling warhead mass-production.<br>
 Do you think something else would give it away, or the bomb production? Everything else could be camoflaged (Some giant construction project...), but Pu enrichment and bomb production would be the hard part.<br>
 I wonder just how far along it would get, if everything else was adequately camoflaged, before the NSA or DIA  (alphabet soup administration) put 2+2 together, and somebody came up with the crazy idea that &quot;they're actually building a huge ship, and these bombs are the fuel!&quot;<br>
 The US could do it, just by keeping few people involved in everything. Only tell workers what they need to know to build something according to these plans. I don't think anybody else on the planet has the intel &amp; spy satellite network that Uncle Sam has, so they'd have a better time of it.<br>
<br>
 Possibly Russia. They've got the space expertise and expertise for secrecy and the nationalistic pride -and they've got tons of weapons grade stuff lying around!<br>
 Questions: economy, leaks due to money from outside, and Murphy's law overcoming the camoflage and giving it away.<br>
<br>
Of course, launch would be a dead giveaway. No more secrets about it. The lack of a definite orbital trajectory track is an interesting point. It would be a while before anyone knows where it's going, and it could change at will.<br>
 Establish a lunar base for _____(fill in the blank -Microsoft?!?) in one shot.<br>
 I still like an NEA as the first. Metals and ices, all in better ores than the Moon, more easily accessable than the Moon. Once anybody spends several hundred million doing feasibility studies for a base to be planted by an Orion, they'd realize that an asteroid gives them better payback than even the political &amp; &quot;traditional thinking&quot; coup of landing on the Moon.<br>
<br>
 I like the idea mentioned in the book (and here, long before the book) to build Orions with blank holes for the bomb storage &amp; feed-paths, to have them ready to fuel up &amp; go in case of an asteroid threat.<br>
<br>
 Note that in all cases, the cargo is another hard part. Lots of specialized stuff... Another reason I like Russia, though China is catching up.<br>
